            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mei-Lin Harrison is a product of San Francisco\u2019s unique cultural fusion. Born in the Sunset District to an American architect father and a mother who had emigrated from Shanghai, Mei-Lin\u2019s childhood was a blend of American suburbia and rich Chinese tradition. She grew up navigating two worlds, her father teaching her about the city's structural bones while her mother shared stories of its hidden histories. This dual perspective instilled in her a deep fascination with how cities work, not just as grids of steel and concrete, but as living ecosystems of people.\n\nThe true turning point in her life was the 1989 Loma Prieta earthquake. At eleven years old, she witnessed the fragility of the city\u2019s lifelines\u2014the collapsed freeways and the fractured Bay Bridge. The event transformed her abstract interest into a concrete mission: to build a more resilient and equitable city. She pursued this passion at UC Berkeley, earning a Master of Urban Planning, her thesis focused on post-disaster transit recovery.\n\nHer career has been a steady, deliberate climb. She started as a junior planner, driven by an idealism that survived years of bureaucratic challenges. Now, as Director of Transit Planning, she fights daily battles over budgets, routes, and public opinion. This demanding career contributed to her amicable divorce years ago; her ex-husband never fully understood why she\u2019d rather attend a late-night community meeting than a gallery opening.\n\nToday, Mei-Lin lives in a sleek Hayes Valley apartment filled with city maps and books on urban theory. Her daily 1.5-mile MUNI commute is both her routine and her field research, where she observes passenger flow and system inefficiencies firsthand. Her social life is a small, tight-knit circle of friends, and she remains deeply connected to her aging mother. Her aspiration isn\u2019t a bigger title, but a legacy: a fully-integrated, world-class public transit system that makes San Francisco truly accessible for everyone. She still sees the city through the eyes of that eleven-year-old girl, determined to ensure its heart never stops beating."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was eleven, huddled with her mother in their Sunset home as the world shook violently. The true terror came later, watching the news: the broken Bay Bridge, the pancaked freeway. Her father tried to explain shear stress and liquefaction, but all Mei-Lin saw were severed arteries. In that moment, the city ceased to be a playground and became a fragile, living body. She felt an overwhelming, fierce need to learn how to keep its heart from ever stopping again. This memory became the bedrock of her mission.\n\n2.\nOn a rare clear day around age eight, her father took her to walk the Golden Gate Bridge, explaining the marvel of its suspension cables. Later that week, her mother brought her to the same spot. She didn't point at the steel, but at the churning water below, telling stories of the first immigrants who saw it as a gateway. Mei-Lin stood between the tangible structure and the invisible history, realizing a city wasn\u2019t just one or the other, but the synthesis of both.\n\n3.\nEarly in her career, she sat through a hostile three-hour meeting in the Mission about extending a bus line by two blocks. The room was hot, the anger palpable. But an elderly woman finally stood up and said, in Spanish, that those two blocks meant she could finally get groceries on her own. Mei-Lin saw the abstract line on her map transform into a lifeline. It was a humbling reminder that her work wasn\u2019t about elegantly drawn routes, but about human dignity.\n\n4.\nShe remembers the night it became clear her marriage was over. He stood in the doorway, handsome in a tailored jacket, waiting for a gallery opening she was missing. She was pulling on her coat to attend a late-night community meeting in Bayview. \"It's just a bus route, Mei,\" he said, not unkindly. But it wasn't just a bus route. The quiet sadness of their divergence was immense, but so was the clarity. In that moment, she understood she was married to the city itself.\n\n5.\nLast month, she took her aging mother on the T Third Street light rail, a line she had fought for years to improve. Her mother, who once navigated a new country on foot, looked out the window at the seamless glide through neighborhoods she hadn't seen in years. She patted Mei-Lin\u2019s hand and said, \u201cThe city feels kinder now.\u201d For Mei-Lin, that simple observation was more validating than any award. It was the legacy she was building, one quiet ride at a time."
